Hope this helps someone else down the line too, but it's the Rigid Body Component interfering with the collision detection somehow.. Not sure why. But removing the Rigid Body Component on the Cannibal will fix the Axe not damaging the Cannibal.

EDIT: And when I got to 6 and a half hours, he uses rigid body.. Found that by making it kinematic (by checking the box in the Unity Inspector) fixes this. It's about Rigid Body combining your hit boxes into one merged composite box. Making it Kinematic, breaks that apart again. You'll need to switch off Kinematic in the HealthScript before you apply torque though, otherwise it won't animate since Kinematic mode disables animation by applying physics:

Rigidbody rBody = GetComponent<Rigidbody>();
rBody.isKinematic = false;
rBody.AddTorque(-transform.forward * 50f);

3 possible things that this happens:

1. You did not using UnityEngine.AI;
2. You forgot the private NavMeshAgent navAgent;
3. You are using an old version of Unity which has only navAgent.Stop(true); instead of the isStopped.

Also check for typos ;) 
